               <msContents>
                  <summary>Ll. 1-4 originally contained a complete recipe, as shown by the double-curved lines in the first hand, that of the scribe, cf. electronic version of 21 a-m. They were the last lines of a page of a codex. The content and the use of the recipe remains unclear due to the small amount of text still extant.</summary>
                  <msItemStruct>
                     <note type="general">Location: Ann Arbor</note>
                     <note type="general">Pub. status: Recto</note>
                     <note type="related">-</note>
                  </msItemStruct>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc>
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>1 papyrus ; 5 x 7 cm.</support>
                        <condition>
                           <ab type="conservation">Regularly cut off at the left and at the top. Papyrus complete.</ab>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>
                           <ab type="lines">1-8</ab>
                           <ab type="recto-verso">Source of description: G; Recto</ab>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <p>For a general description of the palaeography, see electronic version of 21 a-m. Contains writing in both hands, cf. electronic version of 21 a-m. Two double-curved lines are clearly written in the first hand to separate recipes. The second hand begins after the second double-curved line. One diaeresis in l. 7 and a paragraphos  after l. 6. Lot of margin in the left had side, in ll. 1-4 approximately 3 cm. and in ll. 5-8 approximately 2cm.; unfortunately too little text remains for a meaningful translation.</p>
                  </handDesc>
